    <div class="protocol-card">
      <div class="header">
        <h1>Ch. 5 🚨 Critical Care</h1>
        <p>Shock Recognition &amp; Resuscitation • Vasopressors &amp; Inotropes • Invasive Hemodynamics • Mechanical Ventilation • ARDS</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Opening Map -->
      <div class="intro">
        <div class="intro-h"><h2 style="margin:0">📋 Opening Map — What the Chapter Covers</h2></div>
        <div class="grid-2" style="margin-bottom:20px;">
          <div class="callout scope">
            <h3 style="margin:0 0 10px 0; color: var(--blueDeep); font-size:16px;">🎯 Scope</h3>
            <p style="margin:0; font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">Rapid identification and initial management of <strong>hypovolemic, distributive (septic/anaphylactic/neurogenic), cardiogenic, and obstructive shock</strong>; choosing pressors/inotropes; reading <strong>PCWP/CI/SVR</strong>; setting and titrating the ventilator; diagnosing and treating <strong>ARDS</strong>.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="callout times">
            <h3 style="margin:0 0 10px 0; color:#f57c00; font-size:16px;">⏰ Time-Critical Nuggets</h3>
            <ul style="font-size:14px;">
              <li><strong>ABCs first</strong>; fluids early in most shock states</li>
              <li><strong>Norepinephrine</strong> is the workhorse vasopressor for septic shock</li>
              <li>Avoid fluids in acute <strong>cardiogenic shock</strong> or TBI with severe ICP</li>
              <li><strong>Golden hour</strong> for sepsis: cultures + antibiotics within 1 hour</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="callout themes">
          <h3 style="margin:0 0 12px 0; color:#7b1fa2; font-size:16px;">🔥 High-Yield Themes</h3>
          <div class="grid-2" style="gap:15px;">
            <ul style="margin:0;">
              <li><strong>Clinical signs:</strong> Warm skin → distributive; cold/clammy → hypo-, cardio-, or obstructive shock</li>
              <li><strong>Bradycardic shock:</strong> think neurogenic</li>
              <li>NS in very large volumes → hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis; prefer <strong>LR for big boluses</strong></li>
            </ul>
            <ul style="margin:0;">
              <li><strong>PCWP</strong> (preload, left heart, bad if &gt;18) up in cardiogenic/obstructive, down in hypovolemic</li>
              <li><strong>PaO₂/FiO₂ &lt; 200</strong> + bilateral infiltrates + PCWP ≤ 18 → ARDS</li>
              <li><strong>Vent settings:</strong> Vt 6–8 mL/kg IBW; FiO₂ ≤ 60%; PEEP 5</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Base Cases -->
      <div class="content">
        <!-- Case 1: Septic Shock -->
        <div class="case">
          <div class="case-header">🔥 Base Case 1<br>"Hot, hypotensive, confused"</div>
          <div class="patient-info">
            <strong>Patient:</strong> 68-year-old man, fever and cough for 3 days, confused, BP 78/40, HR 126, RR 28, T <span class="temperature">39.4°C</span>, warm extremities, bounding pulses, UOP scant<br/>
            <strong>Exam:</strong> Warm, flushed skin; no JVD; coarse breath sounds in RLL
          </div>
          <div class="section differential">
            <div class="section-title">🔍 Top Differential</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Septic shock</strong> (PNA) most likely from pneumonia; anaphylaxis (no exposure/urticaria), adrenal crisis, neurogenic shock (no bradycardia/SCI)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section next-step">
            <div class="section-title">⚡ Next Best Step</div>
            <ul>
              <li>Large-bore IV/IO, <strong>balanced crystalloid bolus</strong> (LR, 30 mL/kg), send cultures, start <strong>broad-spectrum antibiotics within the golden hour</strong></li>
              <li>Search for source, give <strong>norepinephrine if MAP &lt; 65</strong> after fluids</li>
              <li>Glucose control (target &lt;180). UOP monitoring</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section findings">
            <div class="section-title">📊 Add Data: Lactate 5.2; BP stays 82/44 after 30 mL/kg LR bolus</div>
            <ul>
              <li>Start <strong>norepinephrine</strong> (first-line vasopressor), consider vasopressin add-on if refractory</li>
              <li>Evaluate for source control (drain empyema, remove infected line)</li>
              <li><span class="highlight">Avoid dopamine</span> as the first pressor - less effective and more arrhythmogenic</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section what-if">
            <div class="section-title">🔀 Alternate Forks</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Immunosuppressed/neutropenic:</strong> keep broadest coverage; early source control</li>
              <li><strong>Atrial fibrillation w/ RVR:</strong> cautiously control rate (esmolol), treat sepsis first</li>
              <li><strong>Pulmonary edema after large fluids:</strong> transition earlier to pressors; consider diuretics once perfusion restored</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section takeaway">
            <div class="section-title">🎯 Takeaways &amp; Traps</div>
            <ul>
              <li><span class="highlight">SEPSIS BUNDLE:</span> 30 mL/kg LR, norepinephrine to MAP ≥65, antibiotics within 1 hour, source control</li>
              <li>Don't delay antibiotics for imaging</li>
              <li>Warm skin in shock = distributive</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Case 2: Hypovolemic Shock -->
        <div class="case">
          <div class="case-header">🩸 Base Case 2<br>"Pale, cool, post-trauma"</div>
          <div class="patient-info">
            <strong>Patient:</strong> 24-year-old after MVC; HR 140, BP 84/50, cool clammy skin, anxious, UOP minimal<br/>
            <strong>Exam:</strong> Diffuse abdominal tenderness; no breath sounds in the L apex
          </div>
          <div class="section differential">
            <div class="section-title">🔍 Top Differential</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Hypovolemic hemorrhagic shock</strong> (likely from abdominal bleeding) ± tension pneumothorax</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section next-step">
            <div class="section-title">⚡ Next Best Step</div>
            <ul>
              <li>Two large-bore IVs, <strong>LR bolus</strong> while activating hemorrhage control—call surgery, activate <strong>MTP</strong></li>
              <li>Consider blood if class III–IV shock</li>
              <li><strong>Treat tension pneumothorax if suspected</strong> (needle → chest tube) before x-ray</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section findings">
            <div class="section-title">📊 Add Data: FAST positive; BP transiently improves, then drops</div>
            <ul>
              <li><span class="critical">Urgent operative/IR control of bleeding IMMEDIATELY</span></li>
              <li>Type &amp; cross; <strong>balanced transfusion</strong> if massive hemorrhage (1:1:1)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section takeaway">
            <div class="section-title">💡 Pearls</div>
            <ul>
              <li>Cold, clammy = non-distributive shock</li>
              <li>NS in huge volume → hyperchloremic acidosis—<strong>prefer LR</strong></li>
              <li><strong>UOP ≥0.5 mL/kg/hr</strong> = key resuscitation endpoint</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Case 3: Neurogenic Shock -->
        <div class="case">
          <div class="case-header">🧠 Base Case 3<br>"Bradycardic shock after C-spine injury"</div>
          <div class="patient-info">
            <strong>Patient:</strong> 35yo fall; flaccid paralysis below C6; BP 78/40, HR 52; warm skin, no JVD<br/>
            <strong>Classic Triad:</strong> Hypotension + Bradycardia + Warm Skin
          </div>
          <div class="section findings">
            <div class="section-title">🎯 Diagnosis</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Neurogenic shock</strong> from cervical cord injury</li>
              <li>Loss of sympathetic tone → vasodilation + bradycardia</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section next-step">
            <div class="section-title">⚡ ABCDE Approach</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Airway:</strong> Protect early—high spinal injury risk</li>
              <li><strong>Breathing:</strong> Assess; early intubation if needed</li>
              <li><strong>Circulation:</strong> IV fluids; if unresponsive, start vasopressors (norepi or phenyl)</li>
              <li><strong>Atropine</strong> for profound bradycardia</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section takeaway">
            <div class="section-title">💡 Management Sequence</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Step 1:</strong> Fluids</li>
              <li><strong>Step 2:</strong> Atropine for bradycardia</li>
              <li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Vasopressors for persistent hypotension</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Case 4: Cardiogenic Shock -->
        <div class="case">
          <div class="case-header">💔 Base Case 4<br>"Crushing chest pain with pulmonary edema"</div>
          <div class="patient-info">
            <strong>Patient:</strong> 64-year-old with acute MI; BP 86/54, HR 118, cool, clammy, JVD, rales, S3<br/>
            <strong>Hemodynamics:</strong> PCWP 24, CI 1.6, SVR high
          </div>
          <div class="section findings">
            <div class="section-title">🎯 Type of Shock</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Cardiogenic shock</strong> 2/2 MI (PCWP ↑, CO ↓, SVR ↑)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section next-step">
            <div class="section-title">⚡ First Steps</div>
            <ul>
              <li>O₂, analgesia; correct K/Mg</li>
              <li><strong>Norepi for MAP</strong>, add dobutamine for CO if needed</li>
              <li><strong>Revascularization</strong> (PCI/CABG); <strong>IABP</strong> if refractory</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Case 5: Obstructive Shock -->
        <div class="case">
          <div class="case-header">🚫 Base Case 5<br>"Sudden PEA arrest after femur fracture"</div>
          <div class="patient-info">
            <strong>Patient:</strong> 38-year-old POD1 ORIF; sudden dyspnea → PEA
          </div>
          <div class="section next-step">
            <div class="section-title">⚡ Next Best Step</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Immediate ACLS</strong></li>
              <li>Unstable suspected PE → <strong>thrombolysis</strong> or embolectomy</li>
              <li>Tension PTX → <strong>needle decompression now</strong></li>
              <li>Tamponade → <strong>pericardiocentesis</strong></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section takeaway">
            <div class="section-title">💡 Principle</div>
            <ul><li><strong>Obstructive shock = remove the obstruction</strong></li></ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Case 6: Mechanical Ventilation -->
        <div class="case">
          <div class="case-header">🫁 Base Case 6<br>"You just intubated—what vent settings?"</div>
          <div class="patient-info">
            <strong>Patient:</strong> 72-year-old septic with increased WOB → intubated
          </div>
          <div class="section next-step">
            <div class="section-title">⚡ Initial Vent Settings</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>AC</strong> mode • RR 12–16 • Vt 6–8 mL/kg IBW • FiO₂ 100% → titrate ≤60% • PEEP 5</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section management">
            <div class="section-title">🔧 Adjustments</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>PaCO₂ (ventilation):</strong> change minute ventilation (RR/Vt)</li>
              <li><strong>PaO₂ (oxygenation):</strong> change FiO₂ and/or PEEP</li>
              <li>Watch barotrauma, ↓preload hypotension, VAP</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Case 7: ARDS -->
        <div class="case">
          <div class="case-header">💨 Base Case 7<br>"Refractory hypoxemia + bilateral opacities"</div>
          <div class="patient-info">
            <strong>Patient:</strong> 55-year-old with pancreatitis; PaO₂/FiO₂ 150; PCWP 12
          </div>
          <div class="section findings">
            <div class="section-title">🎯 Diagnosis</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>ARDS</strong> (bilateral opacities + PaO₂/FiO₂ &lt; 200 + PCWP ≤ 18 + acute onset)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="section next-step">
            <div class="section-title">⚡ Management</div>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Low Vt (6 mL/kg)</strong>, adequate PEEP, treat cause; FiO₂ ≤ 60% when possible</li>
              <li>Consider <strong>proning</strong> if refractory</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Template B: Hemodynamics/Imaging/Labs -->
      <div class="intro">
        <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--amber) 0%, var(--amberDeep) 100%);">📊 Template B — Hemodynamics/Imaging/Labs</div>
        <div class="tiles">
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--green);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--green);">PCWP (PA catheter)</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">
              <p><strong>Shows:</strong> LV end-diastolic surrogate (preload)</p>
              <p><strong>Indications:</strong> Differentiate cardiogenic vs ARDS; unclear volume status</p>
              <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> PCWP &gt;18 favors CHF; ≤18 favors ARDS. Use with CO/SVR to profile shock</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--blue);">Cardiac Output / CI</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">
              <p><strong>Shows:</strong> Pump performance</p>
              <p><strong>Use:</strong> Shock of unclear etiology</p>
              <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> Low CI + high SVR → cardiogenic; low CI + low SVR → distributive</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--indigo);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--indigo);">SVR (Systemic Vascular Resistance)</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">
              <p><strong>Shows:</strong> Systemic tone (afterload)</p>
              <p><strong>Use:</strong> Profiling shock</p>
              <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> Very low SVR → distributive. Combine with CI/PCWP</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--magenta);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--magenta);">CXR</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">
              <p><strong>Shows:</strong> Edema, PTX, lines</p>
              <p><strong>Indications:</strong> Dyspnea, vent complications</p>
              <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> New tension PTX → immediate needle decompression</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--amber);">ABG</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px; line-height:1.55;">
              <p><strong>Shows:</strong> Oxygenation/ventilation status</p>
              <p><strong>Use:</strong> Adjust vent settings</p>
              <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> PaO₂ low → ↑FiO₂/PEEP; PaCO₂ high → ↑minute ventilation</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Template C: Pharmacology (Pressors/Inotropes) -->
      <div class="intro">
        <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--magenta) 0%, var(--magentaDeep) 100%);">💊 Template C — Pharmacology (Pressors/Inotropes)</div>
        <div class="tiles" style="grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(350px, 1fr));">
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--green);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--green);">Norepinephrine (Levophed)</div>
            <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
              <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 0.02–0.3 μg/kg/min</p>
              <p><strong>MOA:</strong> α1≫β1 (vasoconstrictor with modest inotropy)</p>
              <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> First-line in septic shock</p>
              <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Ischemia, arrhythmias</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--indigo);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--indigo);">Dobutamine (Dobutrex)</div>
            <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
              <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 2–20 μg/kg/min</p>
              <p><strong>MOA:</strong> β1&gt;β2 (inotrope, mild vasodilation)</p>
              <p><strong>Use:</strong> Cardiogenic shock with low output</p>
              <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Tachyarrhythmias, hypotension</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--amber);">Milrinone (Primacor)</div>
            <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
              <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 0.125–0.5 μg/kg/min</p>
              <p><strong>MOA:</strong> PDE-3 inhibitor (inodilator)</p>
              <p><strong>Use:</strong> For HF/cardiogenic when dobutamine inadequate</p>
              <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Hypotension, arrhythmias; renal dosing</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--red);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--red);">Epinephrine</div>
            <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
              <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 0.02–0.2 μg/kg/min</p>
              <p><strong>MOA:</strong> β1/β2 + α (dose-dependent)</p>
              <p><strong>Use:</strong> Anaphylaxis, refractory septic shock, arrest</p>
              <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Tachyarrhythmias, lactate rise</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--blue);">Phenylephrine (Neo-Synephrine)</div>
            <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
              <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 0.2–1 μg/kg/min</p>
              <p><strong>MOA:</strong> Pure α1 vasoconstrictor</p>
              <p><strong>Use:</strong> Vasodilatory or neurogenic shock, anesthesia-induced hypotension</p>
              <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Reflex bradycardia, ischemia</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--purple);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--purple);">Dopamine (Intropin)</div>
            <div style="font-size:13px; line-height:1.45;">
              <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 5–20 μg/kg/min</p>
              <p><strong>MOA:</strong> Dose-dependent (β1 then α1)</p>
              <p><strong>Pearl:</strong> Replaced by norepinephrine in sepsis; avoid low-dose "renal protection"</p>
              <p><strong>AEs:</strong> Arrhythmias; "renal dose" myth</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Algorithms -->
      <div class="intro">
        <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--purple) 0%, var(--indigo) 100%);">🔄 Algorithms (Diagnostic &amp; Management)</div>
        <div class="alg-grid">
          <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--green);">
            <div class="h" style="background: var(--green);">🚨 A. Undifferentiated Hypotension (Shock)</div>
            <div class="center">ABCs → O₂ → monitors → 2 large-bore IV/IO</div>
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <div class="center"><strong>Give balanced crystalloid bolus</strong> (500–1,000 mL)</div>
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <ul style="font-size:14px;">
              <li><strong>Warm + bounding pulse</strong> → distributive (sepsis → abx + norepi; anaphylaxis → epi, H1/H2, steroids)</li>
              <li><strong>Cold/clammy, narrow PP</strong> → hypo-/cardio-/obstructive (trauma → MTP; cardiogenic → norepi ± dobutamine; obstructive → treat tamponade/PTX/PE)</li>
            </ul>
            <div style="margin-top:10px; font-weight:700; font-size:14px;">
              <strong>Targets:</strong> MAP ≥65, UOP ≥0.5 mL/kg/h, clearing lactate, improving mentation
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--red);">
            <div class="h" style="background: var(--red);">🔥 B. Septic Shock—First Hour</div>
            <ol style="font-size:14px;">
              <li>Blood cultures (don’t delay therapy)</li>
              <li>Broad-spectrum antibiotics</li>
              <li>30 mL/kg balanced crystalloid</li>
              <li>Norepinephrine if MAP &lt;65 after fluids (± vasopressin)</li>
              <li>Source control ASAP; glucose &lt;180; monitor UOP &amp; lactate</li>
            </ol>
          </div>

          <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
            <div class="h" style="background: var(--amber);">🧠 C. Neurogenic Shock</div>
            <div class="center">Fluids → if persistent hypotension with bradycardia</div>
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <ul style="font-size:14px;">
              <li><strong>Norepi or phenyl</strong>; maintain spinal perfusion</li>
              <li><strong>Atropine</strong> for profound bradycardia</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
            <div class="h" style="background: var(--blue);">💔 D. Cardiogenic Shock (AMI)</div>
            <div class="center">O₂, analgesia → correct K/Mg</div>
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <ul style="font-size:14px;">
              <li><strong>Norepi for MAP</strong> → add dobutamine for inotropy</li>
              <li><strong>Early revascularization</strong> ± IABP if refractory</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--purple);">
            <div class="h" style="background: var(--purple);">🐝 E. Anaphylaxis</div>
            <ul style="font-size:14px;">
              <li><strong>Epinephrine</strong> → H1/H2 blockers → steroids</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="alg" style="border-color: #2e7d32;">
            <div class="h" style="background: #2e7d32;">🫁 F. Mechanical Vent—Initial &amp; Adjustments</div>
            <div class="center"><strong>Initial:</strong> AC; RR 12–16; Vt 6–8 mL/kg; FiO₂ 100% → ≤60%; PEEP 5</div>
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <ul style="font-size:14px;">
              <li>Low PaO₂ → ↑FiO₂ or ↑PEEP</li>
              <li>High PaCO₂/low pH → ↑minute ventilation (↑RR or ↑Vt)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--indigo);">
            <div class="h" style="background: var(--indigo);">💨 G. ARDS</div>
            <div class="center"><strong>Criteria:</strong> bilateral infiltrates + PaO₂/FiO₂ &lt; 200 + PCWP ≤ 18 + acute onset</div>
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <div class="center"><strong>Management:</strong> low Vt (6 mL/kg), adequate PEEP, FiO₂ ≤60%, treat cause; consider proning</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Pitfalls & Look-Alikes -->
      <div class="intro" style="border-bottom:3px solid #ecf0f1;">
        <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--red) 0%, #d32f2f 100%);">⚠️ Pitfalls &amp; Look-Alikes — NBME Trap Deck</div>
        <div class="pit-grid">
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--red);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--red);">Early Shock Recognition</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">
              <p>The first sign of hypovolemic shock is <strong>tachycardia</strong> (not hypotension).</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--blue);">Warm vs Cold Shock</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">
              <p><strong>"Warm shock" = distributive</strong>. Others are "cold."</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--teal);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--teal);">Dopamine Myth</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">
              <p>Low-dose <strong>"renal dopamine"</strong> doesn’t protect kidneys.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--purple);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--purple);">Normal Saline Trap</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">
              <p>Large NS → <strong>hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis</strong>; prefer LR for big boluses.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: #2e7d32;">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: #2e7d32;">Neurogenic Clue</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">
              <p><strong>Shock + bradycardia → neurogenic</strong> until proven otherwise.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--indigo);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--indigo);">PEEP Effects</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">
              <p>PEEP improves oxygenation but can <strong>drop preload → hypotension</strong>.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--red);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--red);">Vent Adjustments</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">
              <p><strong>PaCO₂ = ventilation;</strong> <strong>PaO₂ = oxygenation</strong>.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--amber);">ARDS vs CHF</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">
              <p><strong>PCWP ≤18</strong> with bilateral infiltrates → ARDS, not CHF.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--magenta);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--magenta);">Sepsis Delays</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">
              <p>Don’t delay <strong>antibiotics</strong> for cultures/imaging in septic shock.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--blue);">Resuscitation Fluids</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">
              <p><strong>Dextrose-containing fluids are not for initial resuscitation.</strong></p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Micro Pearls & Numbers -->
      <div class="intro">
        <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--indigo) 0%, var(--indigoDeep) 100%);">💎 Micro Pearls &amp; Numbers Worth Memorizing</div>
        <div class="micro-grid">
          <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--red);">
            <div class="h" style="background: var(--red);">ABCs &amp; Intubation</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">ABCs always first; <span class="highlight">GCS ≤ 8 → intubate</span>.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
            <div class="h" style="background: var(--blue);">UOP Target</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">Urine output target: <span class="highlight">≥0.5 mL/kg/hr</span> (adults).</div>
          </div>
          <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--green);">
            <div class="h" style="background: var(--green);">Shock Hemodynamics</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">
              <strong>Hypovolemic:</strong> PCWP ↓, CO ↓, SVR ↑<br/>
              <strong>Cardiogenic/obstructive:</strong> PCWP ↑, CO ↓, SVR ↑<br/>
              <strong>Neurogenic:</strong> PCWP ↓, CO ↓, SVR ↓<br/>
              <strong>Distributive:</strong> PCWP ↓/N, CO ↑, SVR ↓
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="alg" style="border-color: var(--purple);">
            <div class="h" style="background: var(--purple);">Vent Starting Point</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">AC, RR 12–16, <span class="highlight">Vt 6–8 mL/kg (IBW)</span>, FiO₂ 100% → ≤60%, PEEP 5.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="alg" style="border-color: #5d4037;">
            <div class="h" style="background: #5d4037;">ARDS Criteria</div>
            <div style="font-size:14px;">Bilateral infiltrates, <span class="highlight">PaO₂/FiO₂ &lt; 200</span>, PCWP ≤ 18, acute onset.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Rapid Fire Exam Tips & Vignettes -->
      <div class="intro" style="border-bottom:3px solid #ecf0f1;">
        <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #ff5722 0%, #bf360c 100%);">🚀 Rapid Fire Exam Tips &amp; Vignettes</div>
        <div class="rf-grid">
          <!-- (Items 1–15 exactly as in your source; kept for brevity) -->
          <!-- Keep the same content you provided; it will render with the shared styles -->
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Final Wrap -->
      <div class="intro">
        <div class="block-h" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--green) 0%, #388e3c 100%);">🎯 Final Wrap</div>
        <div class="tiles" style="grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(350px, 1fr)); gap:20px;">
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--green);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--green);">🚨 Shock Classification</div>
            <ul style="font-size:14px;">
              <li>Classify shock by <strong>skin, HR, and hemodynamics</strong></li>
              <li>Fluids early, then <strong>norepinephrine for distributive</strong></li>
              <li>Treat the cause for cardio/obstructive</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--red);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--red);">📊 Hemodynamic Profiling</div>
            <ul style="font-size:14px;">
              <li>Profile with <strong>PCWP/CI/SVR</strong> when unclear</li>
              <li><strong>PCWP ≤18</strong> with bilateral opacities → ARDS</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--amber);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--amber);">🫁 Ventilator Care</div>
            <ul style="font-size:14px;">
              <li><strong>Vt 6–8 mL/kg IBW</strong>, FiO₂ ≤ 60%, PEEP for oxygenation</li>
              <li>Adjust <strong>minute ventilation for CO₂</strong></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="tile" style="border-color: var(--blue);">
            <div class="t-h" style="background: var(--blue);">⚠️ Key Pitfalls to Avoid</div>
            <ul style="font-size:14px;">
              <li>Dopamine "renal dose"</li>
              <li>Excessive NS</li>
              <li>Delaying antibiotics/source control</li>
              <li>Missing neurogenic bradycardia</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="margin:18px 0 0 0; font-weight:700; text-align:center;">End of Chapter – Critical Care</p>
      </div>
    </div>

